    "body": "## Problem\n\nruntime/lua/vim/diagnostic.lua currently mixes configuration, storage, display, float rendering, navigation helpers, formatting, statusline support, and builtin handler implementations in one file. That makes the implementation harder to navigate and reason about when changing one part of the diagnostic pipeline.\n\n## Solution\n\nSplit the implementation into focused internal modules for config, display, float rendering, jump/list helpers, namespace and storage management, severity/shared utilities, and statusline support.\n\nMove the builtin handlers into runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic/handlers/ and keep runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic.lua as the public facade that lazily dispatches to the split modules, preserving the external vim.diagnostic API.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [],
    "comment_regular_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> runtime/lua/vim/diagnostic.lua currently mixes configuration, storage, display, float rendering, navigation helpers, formatting, statusline support, and builtin handler implementations in one file. That makes the implementation harder to navigate and reason about when changing one part of the diagnostic pipeline.\r\n\r\nI'm not really sure that's true.\r\n\r\nThis PR introduces 10+ new modules. More granularity isn't necessarily more readable. If people actually prefer this, I'm puzzled. It's definitely not the normal practice of this codebase; does that mean we intend to 10x the number of modules in the codebase?\r\n\r\nThere is a giant problem that no one ever sees when they do this kind of thing: synthesis (putting together) is much harder than analysis (breaking apart). \r\n\r\n- things that should be shared will tend not to be shared, because finding where to put them is a pain.\r\n- discovering common concepts becomes harder (hyper-granularity actually degrades discoverability, though it \"feels\" like organization)\r\n\r\n\r\n## Alternative suggestion\r\n\r\nIf the diagnostic module is too big, find the actual big topics that should be split, rather than splitting into the maximum granularity.",
