        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> It's definitely not the normal practice of this codebase; does that mean we intend to 10x the number of modules in the codebase?\n\nIt is normal in this codebase. Lsp has 26 modules and treesitter has 11, both of which I've been heavily involved in structuring. Vim.diagnostic has been the odd one out for a long time.\n\nIf you look you'll see there aren't a bunch of micro modules. Most of them are 100s LOC, only 4 are less than 100 LOC. Believe it or not, vim.diagnostic has had tonnes of feature creep.\n\nSome of the smaller modules were required to keep a hygienic dependency graph.\n\nI also believe not having a structure to begin with made the module very interconnected which lead it to being broken up so much to keep the dependency graph clean. It may be possible to consolidate some of this with deeper refactors.\n\n> If the diagnostic module is too big, find the actual big topics that should be split, rather than splitting into the maximum granularity.\n\nPlease give a more concrete proposal. Look at the code first at review which parts you don't want split. To me it made sense.\n\n\n> things that should be shared will tend not to be shared, because finding where to put them is a pain.\n> discovering common concepts becomes harder (hyper-granularity actually degrades discoverability, though it \"feels\" like organization)\n\nSorry but I think this is quite an extrapolation. This isn't hyper granularity. The original module was over 3000 LOC. It's a significant subsystem.\n\n",
